    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-07-17T11:02:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-07-17T11:02:00-05:00" n="225"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d225">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_FE1">FE</gloss> files, lot 55 D 128: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Joint Chiefs of Staff</gloss> to the
                        Commander in Chief Far East (<persName corresp="#p_CGMW1" type="to"
                            >Clark</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d225fn1">This telegram, drafted during the State-<gloss
                            target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> meeting on July 16 (see <hi rend="italic"
                            >supra</hi>), was concurred in by the Department of State. The Naval
                        Aide to the President advised <persName corresp="#p_BGOTAON1">General
                            Bradley</persName> that President <persName corresp="#p_THS1"
                            >Truman</persName> approved the plan in principle as one to be sent to
                            <gloss target="#t_CINCFE1">CINCFE</gloss> for his comments. (Memorandum
                        by Cams to <persName corresp="#p_BELGCL1">Bolté</persName>, July 17, 1952;
                            <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> files, CCS 383.21 Korea
                        (3—19–45))</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>operational immediate</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-07-17T12:02:00-04:00"
                            >July 17, 1952—12:02 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 913758. From <gloss target="#t_JCS1"
                        >JCS</gloss>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>In discussing here part 2 ur CX 51489<note n="2" xml:id="d225fn2">Dated
                            July 7, <ref target="#pg_380">p. 380</ref>.</note> and possible other
                        alternative plans to resolve <gloss target="#t_POWs1">POW</gloss> issue the
                        fol suggestion has been made: <list>
                            <label>A.</label>
                            <item>We would offer to release all Chi <gloss target="#t_POWs1"
                                    >POWs</gloss> in accord with procedure whereby Commies would
                                send reptvs to UN <gloss target="#t_POWs1">POW</gloss> enclosures to
                                seek to effect repatriation. It would be stipulated that Commies
                                could not use force effect such repatriation. This procedure would
                                be carried out under observation of reptvs of non-participating
                                nation such as India. Those not repatriated would assume some such
                                status as that of refugees or <gloss target="#t_DPs1">DPs</gloss>
                                pending their ultimate disposition.</item>
                            <label>B.</label>
                            <item>Detailed arrangements to incl logistic assistance to be given by
                                UN would be at ur discretion. As to UN prisoners in Commie hands we
                                would be willing either to fol same procedure in Commie-held
                                territory or accept delivery by Commies to UN-held territory
                                provided all were made available to US.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Foregoing is based on assumption that problem of Korean <gloss
                            target="#t_POWs1">POWs</gloss> can be resolved separately by what now
                        appears to be Commie concurrence to liberal interpretation of <gloss
                            target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> of “home” of Koreans not desiring
                        repatriation. If this assumption does not prove to be valid, foregoing
                        proposal re Chinese could be applied all <gloss target="#t_POWs1"
                            >POWs</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Even if not accepted by Commies the making of such offer by the <gloss
                            target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> and its rejection by Commies would place
                        them in an increasingly weak propaganda position by refusing to accept
                        challenge to their charges of forcible retention. Further objective would be
                        to place Commies in position of being required to offer an alternative
                        solution acceptable <pb facs="0446" n="412" xml:id="pg_412"/> to <gloss
                            target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> or unmistakably demonstrate their lack of
                        desire for armistice.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Request ur comments.<note n="3" xml:id="d225fn3">For <persName
                                corresp="#p_CGMW1">Clark</persName>’s comments, see CX 52284, <ref
                                target="#pg_415">p. 415</ref>.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
